      <geography geographyId="34dbbff8-88ce-11de-ad60-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">GLO</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled for the world..</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The Brown-Schlesinger process is one of the most important production processes for sodium tetrahydroborate.In the Brown-Schlesinger-Process methyl borate is added to hydrogenated sodium in mineral oil: </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">4 Na + 2 H2 +B(OCH3)3  → NaBH4 + 3 NaOCH3</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Separation of the sodium methoxide from NaBH4 was accomplished by such methods as extraction with amines, and extraction with water followed by a counterextraction with a solvent, such as 2-aminopropane.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">The sodium and hydrogen for the Brown-Schlesinger process are produced by an electrolysis of NaOH. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">2 NaOH → 2 Na + O2 + H2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">The overall equation for the process:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">4 NaOH + B(OCH3)3 → NaBH4 + 3 NaOCH3 + O2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Baudis, U., Fichte, R.: Boron and Boron Alloys. Published online: 2000. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: http://www.mrw.interscience.wiley.com/emrw/9783527306732/home</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2000-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Time of publications.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="dcf0706c-e8cc-5aad-bbba-4841c06cffcf" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="RP_amount_1" casNumber="16940-66-2" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="8fba72dd-5eec-4081-ac50-680bd7550a9b" productionVolumeAmount="3977552.08191599" productionVolumeMathematicalRelation="RP_amount_1/ BP_amount_1* BP_PV_1">
        <name xml:lang="en">sodium tetrahydridoborate</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">EcoSpold01Location=GLO
Sodium tetrahydroborate is a white crystalline solid. It is stable in dry air, reacting slowly with moisture. A concentrated aqueous solution of NaBH4 stabilized by NaOH is used to reduce hydrogen sulfite to dithionite in the bleaching of ground wood pulp. Also, NaBH4 has extensive and important use as a reducing agent in organic synthesis. Other hydroborates can be obtained by reaction with NaBH4 to give different reductive capabilities (e.g., NaBH3CN).
Additional applications are extensive, e.g., electroless plating, blowing agent for cellular plastics, removal of heavy metals from waste streams, polymerization catalyst, and hydrogen source for fuel cells.</comment>
