      <intermediateExchange id="ce25316f-8e1e-59e6-b747-d16615c6385e" unitId="77ae64fa-7e74-4252-9c3b-889c1cd20bfc" amount="24.146379249806046" sourceId="026b0ec7-c20a-43c6-806d-db5afdeb78e6" sourceYear="2000" sourceFirstAuthor="Gendorf" intermediateExchangeId="759b89bd-3aa6-42ad-b767-5bb9ef5d331d" activityLinkId="2a362a40-b1c0-591a-8bb3-b9d6ab94a192">
        <name xml:lang="en">electricity, medium voltage</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kWh</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">EcoSpold01Location=UCTE
Estimation. This data was taken from a large chemical plant site in Germany producing 2.05 Mt a-1 (intermediates included) of different chemicals. The values for the energy consumption per kg of product of this plant (3.2 MJ kg-1) were used as approximation for the energy consumption of the Brown-Schlesinger process. This total energy demand contains a split of 50% natural gas, 38% electricity and 12% steam from external energy sources. For this dataset all energy used for heat or steam was assumed to be natural gas. For the electricity, a reference of sodium hydroxide electrolysis reports an electricity consumption of 10 kWh per kg sodium is taken into account.

Further references:

Baudis, U., Fichte, R.: Boron and Boron Alloys. Published online: 2000. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: http://www.mrw.interscience.wiley.com/emrw/9783527306732/home</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <lognormal meanValue="24.146379249806046" mu="3.1841344413140606" variance="0.0006" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="0.17859999999999998"/>
          <pedigreeMatrix reliability="4" completeness="5" temporalCorrelation="5" geographicalCorrelation="5" furtherTechnologyCorrelation="5"/>
          <comment xml:lang="en">Estimation</comment>
        </uncertainty>
